	<span class="s1"><i>Katherine Hoffman Haley </i></span><span class="s2">(08/17/1919-12/25/1999) (A-178-1) N/B</span></p>
<p class="p1">
	<span class="s2">A businesswoman, rancher, and philanthropist, Katherine H. Haley was also a member of the Hobson family, daughter of Edith Hobson Hoffman and Walter H. Hoffman, Jr.&nbsp; She managed family real estate and investments and raised champion shorthorn cattle and quarter horses, one of which was President Ronald Reagan’s favorite mount, Mr. Spats.&nbsp; In the area of philanthropy and volunteerism, she was acknowledged as Woman of the Year in Agriculture by the California Museum of Science and Industry in 1970.&nbsp; In 1986, she was given the Milton M. Teague Award for Outstanding Volunteerism, and in 1986, she was grand marshal of the Ventura County Fair Parade.&nbsp; In politics, she was a tireless fund raiser for the Republican Party in Ventura County, was on the Committee to Re-Elect Congressman Bob Lagomarsino throughout his tenure, raised large amounts of money to elect and re-elect Gov. and President Ronald Reagan.&nbsp; She was a founding chairwoman of California’s Racing Hall of Fame.&nbsp; From 1958 to 1999 she served on the board of Community Memorial Hospital in Ventura.&nbsp; She is locally known as probably the primary major fund raiser for and visionary of the Ventura County Museum of History and Art (now Museum of Ventura County).&nbsp; She also owned an exceptional collection of the western art of Edward Borein.</span></p>
